const editorial = {
  heading: "Why We Keep Coming Back to the Socket Camera",
  html: `
<p>Most home security cameras fail for a boring reason. Not because the picture is bad — because they're never actually installed.</p>

<p>Look at what buying a typical outdoor camera really involves. You choose a spot. You drill into brick or weatherboard. You either run a cable to a power point or you accept a battery you'll be pulling down and charging every few months. Somewhere between the drill and the ladder, the camera ends up in a cupboard.</p>

<p>Then there's the second failure, the sneakier one: the battery camera that <em>was</em> installed, went flat in month four, and has been a decorative plastic box ever since. The homeowner believes they're covered. They aren't.</p>

<h3>What changes when the camera lives in a light socket</h3>

<p>Every one of those problems disappears at once. There's already a fitting above your front door, your back step, your garage, your carport. It already has power running to it. The HauSafe screws into it the way a bulb does — and the install is genuinely done in the time it takes to change a lightbulb, because that is literally what you're doing.</p>

<p>It can't go flat, because it's drawing mains power continuously. There's no charging routine to forget. And because it doubles as a working LED bulb, you're not giving up the light to gain the camera — you get both from the same fitting.</p>

<div class="pull-note">The best security camera is the one that's actually mounted, powered and recording six months from now. Most aren't.</div>

<h3>What we looked at across the category</h3>

<p>We weighted verified customer ratings and review volume most heavily — a 4.4-star average from 59 buyers tells you far less than a 4.0 from 1,187, and we've said so plainly on each card above. Then resolution, night vision, how power is supplied, and what's actually in the box.</p>

<p>That last one matters more than people expect. Plenty of cameras arrive needing a memory card you didn't know to buy, or push you toward a monthly cloud subscription to see your own footage. The HauSafe ships with a 64 GB card included — you record locally, from day one, with nothing further to pay.</p>

<h3>Where we'd point you elsewhere</h3>

<p>If the spot you need covered has no light fitting — the far end of a driveway, a fence line, a shed with no power — a socket camera physically can't help you, and no amount of enthusiasm changes that. That's what the <a href="${AMZ("B08VD5TZ4C", "reolink_editorial")}" rel="sponsored nofollow noopener" target="_blank"><strong>Reolink Spotlight Solar</strong></a> at #5 is for: solar and battery powered, mount it anywhere, from a brand with genuine support behind it. It also costs meaningfully more, needs mounting, and has a battery to keep charged — a different kind of purchase entirely.</p>

<p>If sheer review count is your only filter, the <a href="${AMZ("B0BM4M4CV3", "noonkey_editorial")}" rel="sponsored nofollow noopener" target="_blank"><strong>Noonkey 2-pack</strong></a> at #3 carries 1,187 verified ratings — more than anything else here — and gives you two cameras to cover front and back.</p>

<h3>Our verdict</h3>

<p>For the common case — you want a visible, permanently-powered camera over a door or driveway, up today, without tools or a tradesman — the <a href="${HAUSAFE_CPA}" rel="sponsored nofollow noopener" target="_blank"><strong>HauSafe Cam HD</strong></a> is the most practical option we compared. It's currently AUD 99, down from AUD 198, with the memory card and free shipping included.</p>
`,
};

